# Spec-Driven Development with OpenSpec

**Agent Note**: This project uses OpenSpec for spec-driven development workflows.

- **OpenSpec CLI is installed** (v1.3.1+) and operational in this workspace.
- **When the user asks you to implement a feature or change**, you may use OpenSpec to structure the work:
  - `openspec new change <name>` — Create a change proposal with artifacts (proposal.md, design.md, specs/, tasks.md)
  - `openspec status --change <name>` — Check artifact completion status
  - `openspec instructions <artifact> --change <name>` — Get structured guidance for creating an artifact
  - `openspec list` / `openspec show <name>` — View active changes and specs
  - `openspec archive <name>` — Archive a completed change and merge specs into main
  - `openspec validate <name>` — Validate change structure and specs format

- **How to use it in this project**: 
  - Project config is in `openspec/config.yaml` — it references ai-specs standards and enforcement rules.
  - Changes live in `openspec/changes/` (active) and `openspec/changes/archive/` (completed).
  - Main specs live in `openspec/specs/` (reference source of truth).
  - When you propose or implement a change, follow the artifacts generated by OpenSpec.
  - The user will guide you through what to build; use OpenSpec to organize requirements, design, and tasks.

- **When NOT required**: The user may ask for changes without triggering OpenSpec workflows (e.g., quick fixes, exploration). Adapt to their request style — if they want structured workflow, use OpenSpec; if they want direct implementation, just code.